  "chunk_index": 15,
  "summary": "Inspectors Claddock and Bacon continue their investigation into the murder. Harold Crickenshaw is questioned, but he provides no useful information and expresses fear regarding newspaper reporters. Claddock then interviews Alfred, who claims to be living on social security while developing a new type of phonograph. Claddock observes that while Alfred's suit appears expensive, it is actually cheap. Alfred suggests that if the victim was from London, the killer must know that the Long Warehouse is a suitable location for secret murders.\n\nBrian Eastley, the widower of Edith Crakenchurch, joins the inquiry. He speculates whether the murder was driven by a \"perversion\" and discusses the Crickenshaw family, noting that Harold is married to a woman of noble descent while Alfred is involved in \"black deals.\" Brian also mentions that Sedgwick attracts many women and had several lovers on Ibiza.\n\nCladdock subsequently interviews Emma Cripsen, noting her calm demeanor and suspecting that the mystery of the stone coffin may be linked to her. He questions her regarding the victim's identity and why she previously assumed the woman was French; Emma denies having any specific reason for the assumption. When Bacon presents a small porcelain powder box, Emma claims she does not recognize it and cannot guess its owner. After the interview, Claddock observes Emma walking away quickly, appearing relieved.",
